In this problem, we will utilize the concept of Equivalent Annual Cost which is a method for estimating the cash flow of two projects that have different lifespans. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equivalent Annual Cost}&=\dfrac{\text{Net present value}}{\text{Annuity factor}}
\end{aligned}$$

To solve for the net present value, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\sum\dfrac{\text{Cash flow}}{(1+\text{required return})^\text{time}}-\text{Initial investment}
\end{aligned}$$

For the Net present value of the old machine, the formula we will use is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\text{Opportunity cost}+\dfrac{\text{Cash flow}}{1+\text{rate}}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{Cash flow} + \text{After-tax salvage value}}{(1+\text{rate})^2}
\end{aligned}$$
